revision.text:
the {{ill|Sothic year|de|Sothisjahr}} always began with 1 Achet. Alternatively, months were sometimes named after the most important festival celebrated during that period. In ''The Calendars of Ancient Egypt'', it is suggested that the names of the months in the administrative calendar were borrowed from those in the lunar calendar.<ref>R. A. Parker: ''The Calendars of Ancient Egypt.'' In: ''Studies in Ancient Oriental Civilization.'' Band 26. Chicago (Illinois) 1950, p. 56 §281.</ref> In the lunar calendar, Techi (transliterated as ''tḫy'') was already used for the first month, whereas in the administrative calendar, the name later evolved into {{ill|Djehuti|de|Djehuti}}, which was eventually {{ill|Hellenized|de|gräzisiert}} as {{ill|Thoth|de|Thot}}.<ref>R. A. Parker: ''The Calendars of Ancient Egypt.'' In: ''Studies in Ancient Oriental Civilization.'' Band 26. Chicago (Illinois) 1950, p. 45 Table 7.</ref>
== References == <references /> * {{Literatur |Titel=The Calendars of Ancient Egypt |Autor={{ill|Richard Anthony Parker|de|Richard Anthony Parker}} |Sammelwerk=Studies in Ancient Oriental Civilization |Band=26 |Verlag=The University of Chicago Press |Ort=Chicago (Illinois) |Datum=1950}} * {{Literatur |Titel=Altägyptische Festdaten. |Autor={{ill|Siegfried Schott|de|Siegfried Schott}} |Hrsg=Akademie der Wissenschaften und der Literatur |Sammelwerk=Abhandlungen der geistes- und sozialwissenschaftlichen Klasse |Nummer=10 |Ort=Mainz |Datum=1950-10-27}}
