{{translated page|de|Sothisjahr|version=227836898|comment=Imported full de history}}

[[File:CompareTropicalYears.png|alt=Definitions for the tropical year|thumb]]
The term ‘’‘Sothis year’’’ (also ‘’’[[Sopdet]] year’’’) originally referred in {{ill|Ancient Egypt|de|Alten Ägypten|qq=draft}} to the {{ill|calendar period|de|Kalenderzeitraum|qq=draft}} between two heliacal risings of the {{ill|star|de|Stern|qq=draft}} [[Sirius]].
== Background == With the beginning of the {{ill|Middle Kingdom|de|Mittleren Reiches|qq=draft}}, the duration of a Sothis year—in connection with the {{ill|Coffin Texts|de|Sargtexte|qq=draft}} and {{ill|diagonal star clock|de|Diagonalsternuhr|qq=draft}}en—was additionally applied to the periods between two {{ill|Sirius culminations|de|Sirius-Kulminationen|qq=draft}} or between two {{ill|akronychic Sirius settings|de|akronychischen Sirius-Untergängen|qq=draft}}.
Before the introduction of the Egyptian administrative calendar, to which the {{ill|Egyptian civil lunar calendar|de|ägyptische bürgerliche Mondkalender|qq=draft}} was oriented, the Egyptians followed the Sothis year, which on average—at 365,250015 days—provided the original division of the Egyptian calendar year and roughly corresponded to the {{ill|Julian calendar|1=Julian calendar|2=ja|3=ユリウス暦|4=zh|5=儒略曆|6=ru|7=Юлианский_календарь|8=de|9=Julianischer_Kalender|10=es|11=Calendario juliano|de|julianischen Kalender|qq=draft}}. The {{ill|seasons|de|Jahreszeiten|qq=draft}} of the Sothis year shifted, compared to the actual {{ill|tropical year|de|Sonnenjahr|qq=draft}}, by approximately one day every 126 years.
{| class=“wikitable” style=“width: 98%; border: 2px solid gray;” |- {{Ägyptologie TblHighlight}} |colspan=“6” style=“text-align:center; background:#FFE39B”|’’‘Comparison of Solar and Sothis Year (Period 2770 to 1500 BC)’’’Jean Meeus: ‘‘Astronomical Algorithms: Applications for Ephemeris Tool 4, 5.’’ Barth, Leipzig 2000 for: ‘‘Ephemeris Tool 4,5’’ according to Jean Meeus: ‘‘Conversion Program, 2001’’. |- {{Ägyptologie TblHighlight}} ! {{ill|Observation site|de|Beobachtungsort|qq=draft}} ! {{ill|1 Sothis year|de|1 Sothisjahr|qq=draft}} ! {{ill|1 solar year|de|1 Sonnenjahr|qq=draft}} ! {{ill|Deviation|de|Abweichung|qq=draft}} ! {{ill|Shift of one day after:|de|Verschiebung von einem Tag nach:|qq=draft}} |- style=“background:#F5F5F5” |{{ill|Nile Delta|de|Nildelta|qq=draft}} |style=“text-align:center” | 365.25001 days |style=“text-align:center” | 365.24208 daysFrom {{ill|summer solstice|de|Sommersonnenwende|qq=draft}} to the next summer solstice, based on the period 2770 BC to 1500 BC. |style=“text-align:center” | 0.0079298 days |style=“text-align:center” | 126 years + 39 days |- style=“background:#FFFAF0” |{{ill|Elephantine|de|Elephantine|qq=draft}} |style=“text-align:center” | 365.25002 days |style=“text-align:center” | 365.24208 days |style=“text-align:center” | 0.0079417 days |style=“text-align:center” | 125 years + 11 months |- |}
== See also == • {{ill|Book of Nut|de|Nutbuch|qq=draft}} • {{ill|Sothis cycle|de|Sothis-Zyklus|qq=draft}}
== Literature == • Rolf Krauss: ‘‘Sothis and Lunar Data: Studies on the Astronomical and Technical Chronology of Ancient Egypt.’’ Gerstenberg, Hildesheim 1985, {{Falsche ISBN|3-8067-8086-X}}. • {{ill|Christian Leitz|de|Christian Leitz|qq=draft}}: ‘‘Studies on Egyptian Astronomy.’’ Harrassowitz, Wiesbaden 1991, ISBN 3-447-03157-3. • {{ill|Alexandra von Lieven|de|Alexandra von Lieven|qq=draft}}: ‘‘Outline of the Course of the Stars: The so-called Book of Nut.’’ The Carsten Niebuhr Institute of Ancient Eastern Studies (among others), Copenhagen 2007, ISBN 978-87-635-0406-5. • {{ill|Siegfried Schott|de|Siegfried Schott|qq=draft}}: ‘‘Ancient Egyptian Festal Dates.’’ Verlag der Akademie der Wissenschaften und der Literatur, Mainz/Wiesbaden 1950.
